data.content:
Here's exactly what happened and how to fix it:

## What broke

C# 14 introduces new **span overload resolution** rules. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, the compiler now binds to `MemoryExtensions.Contains(Span<T>, T)` instead of `Enumerable.Contains(IEnumerable<T>, T)`.

Expression trees **cannot represent span-based method calls**, so this throws at runtime (the expression tree interpreter doesn't know how to handle the `MemoryExtensions` overload).

## How to fix

Force the compiler to bind to `Enumerable.Contains` by treating the array as `IEnumerable<T>`. Any of these work:

```csharp
// Option 1: Cast to IEnumerable<int>
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => ((IEnumerable<int>)array).Contains(num);

// Option 2: Use .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 3: Explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

All three disambiguate away from the span overload and back to `Enumerable.Contains`, which expression trees support.
